While Memphis has a high vacancy rate (14.6%), the county outside the
city has a significantly lower rate of 5.2%. The county saw an increase
of 6,903 occupied units and a decrease in 761 vacant units, meaning at
least 6,142 new units were developed.
The outlying metro’s vacancy rate falls somewhere in the middle at
9.1%. Removing the county’s data reveals that the outlying metro area
saw an increase in the number of vacant units, in contrast to the city
and county. Overall, there was an increase of 12,992 occupied units AND
an increase in 1,696 vacant units. This combination of increased
occupancy and vacancy signifies substantial new development in areas
outside Shelby County–at least 14,688 units.
In total, at least 24,411 new housing units were developed in the
Memphis area from 2010-2020, with development primarily in the metro
area outside Shelby County.
Despite most development occurring outside the city limits, Memphis’
high vacancy rate means there is still a large amount of existing
housing that should be available. However, the quality of these homes
may make them uninhabitable, the area may be undesirable, or the costs
may be too high for existing residents to afford. This information is
outside the scope of this post and further research is needed to draw
any conclusions.
Conclusion
Memphis’s population stagnated between 2010 and 2020, hovering around
635,000 people. Over this same time period, a decrease in average
household size lead to an increase in the number of households. This
means that while the population in the city remained flat, there was
still an increase in the demand for housing over the past decade.
Meanwhile, areas outside the city saw strong population/household
growth. Despite a recent desire by city officials to increase density,
new development over the past decade was primarily in the metro region
outside the county limits. Memphis’s high vacancy rate should mean there
is still a large amount of the existing housing stock available for
occupancy. Further research is needed on the quality, cost, and location
of this housing to determine actual availability.
